          <p class="lead">One of the most frustrating AC problems is when your <strong>air conditioner runs but doesn't cool</strong> your home. You can hear it running, feel air coming from the vents, but your house stays hot and uncomfortable. This common issue has many potential causes, and our Lake Charles technicians have the expertise to diagnose and fix them all.</p>

          <div style="background: #f8f9fa; padding: 1.5rem; border-radius: 8px; margin: 2rem 0; text-align: center;">
            <h2 style="margin-top: 0;">AC Not Cooling? Call Now</h2>
            <p style="font-size: 1.1rem;">Same-Day Service Available</p>
            <a href="tel:+13375134425" style="font-size: 2rem; font-weight: 700; color: #0066cc;">(337) 513-4425</a>
          </div>

          <h2>Why Is My AC Running But Not Cooling?</h2>
          <p>Several issues can cause your AC to run without providing adequate cooling:</p>

          <h3>1. Dirty or Clogged Air Filter</h3>
          <p>A dirty air filter restricts airflow, reducing your system's ability to cool effectively. In severe cases, it can cause the evaporator coil to freeze. Check your filter first - if it's visibly dirty, replace it and see if performance improves.</p>

          <h3>2. Low Refrigerant (Freon)</h3>
          <p>Your AC doesn't "use up" refrigerant - if it's low, you have a <a href="/refrigerant-leak-repair/">refrigerant leak</a>. Low refrigerant reduces cooling capacity and can damage your compressor if not addressed. Signs include:</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Ice forming on refrigerant lines or evaporator coil</li>
            <li>Hissing or bubbling sounds</li>
            <li>Warm air from vents despite AC running</li>
            <li>Higher than normal energy bills</li>
          </ul>

          <h3>3. Frozen Evaporator Coil</h3>
          <p>A <a href="/frozen-evaporator-coil/">frozen evaporator coil</a> can't absorb heat from your home's air. This is usually caused by restricted airflow (dirty filter, blocked vents) or low refrigerant. If you see ice on the indoor unit or refrigerant lines, turn off your AC and call us.</p>

          <h3>4. Dirty Condenser Coils</h3>
          <p>The outdoor unit's condenser coils release heat from your home. When coated with dirt, grass, or debris, they can't release heat efficiently, reducing cooling performance. We clean condenser coils as part of our <a href="/ac-contractor/ac-tune-up/">AC tune-up service</a>.</p>

          <h3>5. Faulty Compressor</h3>
          <p>The <a href="/compressor-repair/">compressor</a> is the heart of your AC system. If it's failing, your system can't circulate refrigerant and won't cool properly. Compressor problems often produce unusual noises or cause the outdoor unit to shut off frequently.</p>

          <h3>6. Thermostat Issues</h3>
          <p>Sometimes the problem isn't with your AC at all - it's the <a href="/thermostat-repair/">thermostat</a>. A malfunctioning thermostat may not signal your AC to cool properly, or may be reading temperatures incorrectly.</p>

          <h3>7. Undersized System</h3>
          <p>If your AC has always struggled to cool your home, especially on the hottest days, it may be undersized for your space. This is common in homes where additions were made without upgrading the HVAC system.</p>

          <h2>What to Check Before Calling</h2>
          <p>Before calling for service, check these items yourself:</p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Thermostat setting:</strong> Ensure it's set to "cool" and the temperature is set below the current room temperature</li>
            <li><strong>Air filter:</strong> Replace if dirty</li>
            <li><strong>Vents:</strong> Make sure supply and return vents aren't blocked by furniture or closed</li>
            <li><strong>Outdoor unit:</strong> Check that it's running and not covered in debris</li>
            <li><strong>Circuit breaker:</strong> Verify the AC breaker hasn't tripped</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Our AC Diagnostic Process</h2>
          <p>When you call Latour's HVAC for an AC not cooling, here's what to expect:</p>
